{"title_page": "Athisayan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Athisayan\n| image          = Athisayan_malayalam.jpg\n| caption        = Athisayan theatrical poster\n| alt            =\n| director       = [[Vinayan]]\n| producer       = [[Gokulam Gopalan]]\n| writer         = [[Vinayan]]\n| starring       = <br />[[Master Devadas]]<br /> [[Jackie Shroff]]<br /> [[Jayasurya]]<br /> [[Kavya Madhavan]]<br /> [[Rajan P Dev]]<br />[[Devan (actor)|Devan]]\n| music          = [[Alphonse Joseph (composer)|Alphonse Joseph]]\n| cinematography = Raaja Ratnam\n| editing        = G. Murali\n| studio         =\n| distributor    = [[Sree Gokulam Movies]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2007|04|17}}\n| runtime        = 135 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Malayalam\n}}\n'''''Athisayan''''' is a 2007 [[Malayalam]] [[science fiction film]] directed by [[Vinayan]], starring Master Devadas, [[Jackie Shroff]], [[Jayasurya]] and [[Kavya Madhavan]] in the lead roles. The film was inspired by the 2003 American [[superhero film]] ''[[Hulk (film)|Hulk]]''. ''Athisayan'' marked the debut of [[Bollywood]] actor Jackie Shroff in Malayalam cinema. The film was dubbed and released in Hindi as ''Naya Ajooba'' in 2009.The film was a great hit in malayalam cinema History. \n\n\n\n<br />\n\n==Plot==\nMaya ([[Kavya Madhavan]]),a young television reporter, works for New India Television. Radharamanan ([[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]), the Managing Director of the channel, has a fascination for Maya, who was brought up in an orphanage by Father Chanthakkadan ([[Thilakan]]).  Maya takes up the responsibility of bringing up a few orphans whom she has picked up from the streets. One of these kids is Devan (Master Murali K), who is sort of a child prodigy, with a computer-like mind and very good in studies and extra-curricular activities. R. C. Shekhar ([[Jackie Shroff]]), a scientist, lives very near their house, with his servant Damodaran ([[Harisree Ashokan]]). He is working on a project, which could help in making human beings invisible. On the very day that he successfully experiments his 'magic' [[potion]] on a rabbit, he is urgently called to the [[United States|U.S]] as his daughter, who is studying there, meets with an accident.\n\nMeanwhile, Maya's friend and lover Roy ([[Jayasurya]]), also a journalist, is in jail after having been framed in a murder case by some influential politicians including the State Revenue Minister Divakaran ([[Rajan P. Dev]]), another minister Yunus Kunju (Ramu), the Police Commissioner Shanmughan ([[Bheeman Raghu]]) and the very influential Kuwait Nazar ([[Devan (actor)|Devan]]). With the help of the newly appointed Collector Anita Williams ([[Karthika Mathew|Murali Bhai]]), Maya shoots a video of these baddies accepting millions of rupees as commission from some Arab businessmen, who are there to sign some business deals with the State Government.\nMaya immediately goes to Radharamanan and shows him the clip. Radharamanan is thrilled and agrees to telecast it, after discussing it with the Board of Directors. Somehow Nazar, Divakaran and others come to know of this and they go after Maya, in order to get from her the memory card containing the clipping. On the very same day that R.C.Shekhar goes to the U.S, Maya is [[Kidnapping|abducted]] by Nazar and group. The kids are baffled. Anita Williams, Father Chanthakkadan and Radharamanan know who are behind this, but nothing can be done without sufficient evidence. And then Devan, who had seen R.C. Shekhar conducting the experiment on the rabbit, steals into Shekhar's lab and drinks the potion. He becomes invisible and sets out to save Maya.\n\nDevan did manage to save Maya, but when yunus tries to shoot Maya, Devan comes in between and gets shot. Due to the potion he gets saved but as side effect of getting shot(which Shekhar warns no metallic objects should make a scratch on him) he turns into a gigantic monster and kills those who has done wrong to him and his family. After killing the baddies, Devan leaves Maya and the children and makes his abode in the deep ocean, with an end note saying that \"to fight for the Justice, Devan will come back as Athisayan\".\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Managing Director Radharamanan\n* Master Devadas as Devan\n* [[Kavya Madhavan]] as Reporter Maya\n* [[Jackie Shroff]] as Scientist Sekhar\n* [[Karthika Mathew|Karthika]] as District Collector Anitha Williams\n* [[Jagadish]] as News-reader Koshy\n* [[Harisree Ashokan]] as Servant Damodaran\n* [[Devan (actor)|Devan]] as Kuwait Nazar\n* [[Thilakan]] as Fr. Chanthakkadan\n* [[Jayasurya]] as Journalist Roy\n* [[Ramu (actor)|Ramu]] as Minister Yunus Kunju\n* [[Rajan P. Dev]] as Revenue Minister  Divakaran\n* [[Guinness Pakru]]\n* [[Baby Nayanthara]] as Maya's beloved girl in orphanage and also minister's illegal child Kingini\n* [[Bheeman Raghu]] as Inspector Shanmughan \nDGP Augustine Kuruvila\n* [[Indrans]]\n*[[T. P. Madhavan]]\nMafia Sasi as Hassan musthafa \n*[[Narayanankutty]]\n* [[Augustine (actor)|Augustine]]\n* [[Tini Tom]] as Jamal\n* [[Sadiq]]\n* [[Mala Aravindan]] as Justice Rama Moorthi\n* Lakshmipriya\n*Usha as Susamma\n*Ponnamma Babu \n*[[Mala Aravindan]] as Ramamoorthy\n*[[Baburaj]] as parunthu johny\n*Augustine as Adv Joy Manjooran\n* Encrypter Vrius\n\n==Production==\nThe shooting of the film was in [[Kerala]], mainly in locations in [[Aluva]] and [[Ernakulam]]. The film was high on [[special effects]], [[visual effects]] and [[2D Animation]]. These special effects of ''Athisayan'' were done at EFX, [[Chennai]].<ref>http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/thscrip/print.pl?file=2006040700840200.htm&date=2006/04/07/&prd=fr&</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''Athisayan'' was released in Kerala during the summer vacation, on 17 April 2007, mainly aiming at children. The target audience of the film were school children, whom the makers of the film expected to come in large numbers to the watch the new [[superhero]].\n\n''Athisayan'' was a flop at the box-office, despite the huge promotional activities prior to its release. The evident resemblance to ''[[Hulk (film)|Hulk]]'' and the comparison to this proved costly for the film. Also the family audience preferred films like ''[[Vinodayathra]]'' and ''[[Big B (film)|Big B]]'' which released at the same time. The film received mainly negative reviews. It received a {{rating|1.5|5}} rating from Nowrunning.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/movie/3013/malayalam/athisayan/1137/review.htm|title=Athisayan Review|date=16 April 2007|work=Nowrunning}}</ref> Metromatinee and Sify.com also gave mainly negative reviews to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=42-Athisayan|title=Athisayan Malayalam Movie Profile, Trailers, Wallpapers, Photos, Cast & Crew, Story & Synopsis, Reviews - metromatinee.com|work=metromatinee.com|access-date=6 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110106232544/http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=42-Athisayan|archive-date=6 January 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/malayalam/review.php?id=14431181&ctid=5&cid=2428|title=Review : Athisayan|work=Sify}}</ref> The makers actually planned a sequel for the film, had ''Athisayan'' become the new [[superhero]] among children. The last scene of the film states that ''\"Athisayan will come back to fight for justice\"''. But with the poor response to the film at the box-office, these plans are dropped.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Athisayan\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Alphonse Joseph\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2007\n| recorded   = Satyam Audios\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[World Music]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Satyam Audios\n| producer   = Sree Gokulam Movies\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe music of Athisayan is by [[Alphonse Joseph (composer)|Alphonse Joseph]]. The lyrics are written by [[Vinayan]] and [[Vayalar Sarath Chandra Varma]]. The film has four songs. The singers are [[Vineeth Sreenivasan]],  [[Rimi Tomy]], [[Vidhu Prathap]],  Balu, Karthik and Sithara.\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #D7D7D5; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#808080\" align=\"center\"\n| '''Track #''' || '''Song''' || '''Singer(s)'''\n|-\n| 1 || \"Aluva Manappurathe\" || [[Sithara Krishnakumar|Sithara]]\n|-\n| 2 || \"Ennomale\" || [[Vineeth Sreenivasan]], [[Rimi Tomy]]\n|-\n| 3 || \"Neeyennomal\" || [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]]\n|-\n| 4 || \"Athishayan (Kuttappanmaaraya)\" || [[Vidhu Prathap]],  Balu\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Science fiction film of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0997033}}\n\n[[Category:2000s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s Indian superhero films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Indian children's films]]\n[[Category:2000s monster movies]]\n[[Category:Fiction about invisibility]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Athisayan\n| image          = Athisayan_malayalam.jpg\n| caption        = Athisayan theatrical poster\n| alt            =\n| director       = [[Vinayan]]\n| producer       = [[Gokulam Gopalan]]\n| writer         = [[Vinayan]]\n| starring       = <br />[[Master Devadas]]<br /> [[Jackie Shroff]]<br /> [[Jayasurya]]<br /> [[Kavya Madhavan]]<br /> [[Rajan P Dev]]<br />[[Devan (actor)|Devan]]\n| music          = [[Alphonse Joseph (composer)|Alphonse Joseph]]\n| cinematography = Raaja Ratnam\n| editing        = G. Murali\n| studio         =\n| distributor    = [[Sree Gokulam Movies]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2007|04|17}}\n| runtime        = 135 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Malayalam\n}}\n'''''Athisayan''''' is a 2007 [[Malayalam]] [[science fiction film]] directed by [[Vinayan]], starring Master Devadas, [[Jackie Shroff]], [[Jayasurya]] and [[Kavya Madhavan]] in the lead roles. The film was inspired by the 2003 American [[superhero film]] ''[[Hulk (film)|Hulk]]''. ''Athisayan'' marked the debut of [[Bollywood]] actor Jackie Shroff in Malayalam cinema. The film was dubbed and released in Hindi as ''Naya Ajooba'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vijsonfilms.com/films/naya_ajooma.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504121652/http://vijsonfilms.com/films/naya_ajooma.htm |archivedate=4 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nMaya ([[Kavya Madhavan]]),a young television reporter, works for New India Television. Radharamanan ([[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]), the Managing Director of the channel, has a fascination for Maya, who was brought up in an orphanage by Father Chanthakkadan ([[Thilakan]]).  Maya takes up the responsibility of bringing up a few orphans whom she has picked up from the streets. One of these kids is Devan (Master Murali K), who is sort of a child prodigy, with a computer-like mind and very good in studies and extra-curricular activities. R. C. Shekhar ([[Jackie Shroff]]), a scientist, lives very near their house, with his servant Damodaran ([[Harisree Ashokan]]). He is working on a project, which could help in making human beings invisible. On the very day that he successfully experiments his 'magic' [[potion]] on a rabbit, he is urgently called to the [[United States|U.S]] as his daughter, who is studying there, meets with an accident.\n\nMeanwhile, Maya's friend and lover Roy ([[Jayasurya]]), also a journalist, is in jail after having been framed in a murder case by some influential politicians including the State Revenue Minister Divakaran ([[Rajan P. Dev]]), another minister Yunus Kunju (Ramu), the Police Commissioner Shanmughan ([[Bheeman Raghu]]) and the very influential Kuwait Nazar ([[Devan (actor)|Devan]]). With the help of the newly appointed Collector Anita Williams ([[Karthika Mathew|Murali Bhai]]), Maya shoots a video of these baddies accepting millions of rupees as commission from some Arab businessmen, who are there to sign some business deals with the State Government.\nMaya immediately goes to Radharamanan and shows him the clip. Radharamanan is thrilled and agrees to telecast it, after discussing it with the Board of Directors. Somehow Nazar, Divakaran and others come to know of this and they go after Maya, in order to get from her the memory card containing the clipping. On the very same day that R.C.Shekhar goes to the U.S, Maya is [[Kidnapping|abducted]] by Nazar and group. The kids are baffled. Anita Williams, Father Chanthakkadan and Radharamanan know who are behind this, but nothing can be done without sufficient evidence. And then Devan, who had seen R.C. Shekhar conducting the experiment on the rabbit, steals into Shekhar's lab and drinks the potion. He becomes invisible and sets out to save Maya.\n\nDevan did manage to save Maya, but when yunus tries to shoot Maya, Devan comes in between and gets shot. Due to the potion he gets saved but as side effect of getting shot(which Shekhar warns no metallic objects should make a scratch on him) he turns into a gigantic monster and kills those who has done wrong to him and his family. After killing the baddies, Devan leaves Maya and the children and makes his abode in the deep ocean, with an end note saying that \"to fight for the Justice, Devan will come back as Athisayan\".\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Managing Director Radharamanan\n* Master Devadas as Devan\n* [[Kavya Madhavan]] as Reporter Maya\n* [[Jackie Shroff]] as Scientist Sekhar\n* [[Karthika Mathew|Karthika]] as District Collector Anitha Williams\n* [[Jagadish]] as News-reader Koshy\n* [[Harisree Ashokan]] as Servant Damodaran\n* [[Devan (actor)|Devan]] as Kuwait Nazar\n* [[Thilakan]] as Fr. Chanthakkadan\n* [[Jayasurya]] as Journalist Roy\n* [[Ramu (actor)|Ramu]] as Minister Yunus Kunju\n* [[Rajan P. Dev]] as Revenue Minister  Divakaran\n* [[Guinness Pakru]]\n* [[Baby Nayanthara]] as Maya's beloved girl in orphanage and also minister's illegal child Kingini\n* [[Bheeman Raghu]] as Inspector Shanmughan \nDGP Augustine Kuruvila\n* [[Indrans]]\n*[[T. P. Madhavan]]\nMafia Sasi as Hassan musthafa \n*[[Narayanankutty]]\n* [[Augustine (actor)|Augustine]]\n* [[Tini Tom]] as Jamal\n* [[Sadiq]]\n* [[Mala Aravindan]] as Justice Rama Moorthi\n* Lakshmipriya\n*Usha as Susamma\n*Ponnamma Babu \n*[[Mala Aravindan]] as Ramamoorthy\n*[[Baburaj]] as parunthu johny\n*Augustine as Adv Joy Manjooran\n* Encrypter Vrius\n\n==Production==\nThe shooting of the film was in [[Kerala]], mainly in locations in [[Aluva]] and [[Ernakulam]]. The film was high on [[special effects]], [[visual effects]] and [[2D Animation]]. These special effects of ''Athisayan'' were done at EFX, [[Chennai]].<ref>http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/thscrip/print.pl?file=2006040700840200.htm&date=2006/04/07/&prd=fr&</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''Athisayan'' was released in Kerala during the summer vacation, on 17 April 2007, mainly aiming at children. The target audience of the film were school children, whom the makers of the film expected to come in large numbers to the watch the new [[superhero]].\n\n''Athisayan'' was a flop at the box-office, despite the huge promotional activities prior to its release. The evident resemblance to ''[[Hulk (film)|Hulk]]'' and the comparison to this proved costly for the film. Also the family audience preferred films like ''[[Vinodayathra]]'' and ''[[Big B (film)|Big B]]'' which released at the same time. The film received mainly negative reviews. It received a {{rating|1.5|5}} rating from Nowrunning.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/movie/3013/malayalam/athisayan/1137/review.htm|title=Athisayan Review|date=16 April 2007|work=Nowrunning}}</ref> Metromatinee and Sify.com also gave mainly negative reviews to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=42-Athisayan|title=Athisayan Malayalam Movie Profile, Trailers, Wallpapers, Photos, Cast & Crew, Story & Synopsis, Reviews - metromatinee.com|work=metromatinee.com|access-date=6 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110106232544/http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=42-Athisayan|archive-date=6 January 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sify.com/movies/malayalam/review.php?id=14431181&ctid=5&cid=2428|title=Review : Athisayan|work=Sify}}</ref> The makers actually planned a sequel for the film, had ''Athisayan'' become the new [[superhero]] among children. The last scene of the film states that ''\"Athisayan will come back to fight for justice\"''. But with the poor response to the film at the box-office, these plans are dropped.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Athisayan\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Alphonse Joseph\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2007\n| recorded   = Satyam Audios\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[World Music]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Satyam Audios\n| producer   = Sree Gokulam Movies\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe music of Athisayan is by [[Alphonse Joseph (composer)|Alphonse Joseph]]. The lyrics are written by [[Vinayan]] and [[Vayalar Sarath Chandra Varma]]. The film has four songs. The singers are [[Vineeth Sreenivasan]],  [[Rimi Tomy]], [[Vidhu Prathap]],  Balu, Karthik and Sithara.\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #D7D7D5; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#808080\" align=\"center\"\n| '''Track #''' || '''Song''' || '''Singer(s)'''\n|-\n| 1 || \"Aluva Manappurathe\" || [[Sithara Krishnakumar|Sithara]]\n|-\n| 2 || \"Ennomale\" || [[Vineeth Sreenivasan]], [[Rimi Tomy]]\n|-\n| 3 || \"Neeyennomal\" || [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]]\n|-\n| 4 || \"Athishayan (Kuttappanmaaraya)\" || [[Vidhu Prathap]],  Balu\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Science fiction film of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0997033}}\n\n[[Category:2000s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s Indian superhero films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Indian children's films]]\n[[Category:2000s monster movies]]\n[[Category:Fiction about invisibility]]\n", "name_user": "103.231.219.154", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athisayan"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Alaska, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 cases in geographical Alaska.jpg\n| legend1         = Map of cases by borough, as of April 18\n{{legend|#FDFEB3|1\u20139}}{{legend|#FCDA74|10\u201359}}{{legend|#B60000|> 60}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n| arrival_date    = March 7, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 314\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| hospitalized_cases = 36\n| recovery_cases  = 147\n| deaths          = 9\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://coronavirus.alaska.gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Alaska]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska's coronavirus response has escalated as the number of cases has grown. Here's where things stand. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/22/alaskas-coronavirus-response-has-escalated-as-the-number-of-cases-has-grown-heres-where-things-stand/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]'s office declared a state of emergency to ensure all entities have the necessary response resources.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/11/governor-issues-public-health-disaster-emergency-declaration-for-covid-19/|title=Governor Issues Public Health Disaster Emergency Declaration for COVID-19|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The next day, the first case, a foreign national in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], was announced to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/12/first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-by-alaska-state-public-health-laboratory-is-an-international-resident/|title=First case of COVID-19 confirmed by Alaska State Public Health Laboratory is an international resident|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Alaska medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Ketchikan, Alaska, Estados Unidos, 2017-08-16, DD 01.jpg|thumb|Ketchikan, one of the places affected by COVID-19 during the 2020 outbreak in Alaska]]\nIn March 21, 2020, [[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]], a small, coastal town of approximately 8,000 residents located in [[Southeast Alaska]] was determined to have a cluster of six COVID-19 cases. The town [[shelter in place|sheltered in place]] for the following 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Stone |title=Officials announce three more COVID-19 cases in Ketchikan |url=https://www.ktoo.org/2020/03/21/ketchikan-officials-announce-three-more-covid-19-cases/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[KRBD]] via [[KTOO-TV]]|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, 2020, three more cases of COVID-19 were found in Ketchikan, bringing the total there to nine.<ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Ketchikan confirms 3 new cases of COVID-19 |url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/Ketchikan-confirms-2-new--confirmed-cases-of-COVID-19-569066131.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[KTUU-TV]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, the total cases there reached 11.<ref>{{cite web|first=Eric|last=Stone|url=https://www.krbd.org/2020/03/25/two-new-coronavirus-cases-bring-ketchikans-total-to-11/ |title=Two new coronavirus cases bring Ketchikan's total to 11 |date=26 March 2020|publisher=[[KRBD]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020, the number of positive cases of COVID-19 in Ketchikan rose to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kinyradio.com/news/news-of-the-north/ketchikan-covid-19-cases-rise-to-14-after-new-diagnosis/ |title=Ketchikan COVID-19 cases rise to 14 after new diagnosis |date=April 1, 2020|publisher=[[KINY]]|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Measures==\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] ordered public schools to close from March 16 to 30,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska officials close public schools to students through March 30 to limit spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/14/alaska-officials-close-k-12-public-schools-to-students-for-extra-2-weeks-to-limit-spread-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\">{{cite news |title=Alaska's statewide school closure is beginning. No one knows quite how it will work. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/education/2020/03/16/alaskas-statewide-school-closure-is-about-to-begin-no-one-knows-quite-how-it-will-work/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> which was later extended to May 1.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\">{{cite news |last1=Hanlon |first1=Tegan |last2=Ruskin |first2=Liz |last3=Media |first3=Alaska Public |title=State extends Alaska school closures as coronavirus count grows to 14 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/20/state-announces-new-business-closures-for-fairbanks-ketchikan-and-asks-alaskans-to-stop-all-non-essential-travel/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> School districts were advised to find ways to use remote learning, but there was concern about the impact on the youngest students, special ed students, and small and remote areas where online learning is more difficult.<ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Dunleavy announced the creation of the Alaska Economic Stabilization Team (AEST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/home/covid-19-economy/|title=COVID-19 Alaska Economic Stabilization Team \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, restaurants were restricted to take-out and delivery, and entertainment venues such as movie theaters and gyms were closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruskin |first1=Liz |title=State bans restaurant dining as Alaska's confirmed coronavirus cases grow to 6 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/17/state-bans-restaurant-dining-as-alaskas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-6/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayor of Anchorage]] [[Ethan Berkowitz]] issued an \"emergency hunker down order\" effective March 22.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some businesses were closed in [[Fairbanks North Star Borough]] and [[Ketchikan Gateway Borough]].<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some villages restricted air travel.<ref name=\"villages 1\">{{cite news |title=Alaska villages to ban, restrict air travel amid coronavirus |url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Alaska-villages-to-ban-restrict-air-travel-amid-15148159.php |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Hour |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"villages 2\">{{cite news |title=Alaska rural villages begin to ban or severely restrict air travel in hopes of slowing coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/rural-alaska/2020/03/20/alaska-rural-villages-begin-to-ban-or-severely-restrict-air-travel-in-hopes-of-slowing-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Mike Dunleavy ordered everyone arriving in Alaska to self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival, effective March 25, with limited exceptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Health Mandate |url=https://gov.alaska.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/03232020-SOA-COVID-19-Health-Mandate-010.pdf |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |last3=Bogel-Burroughs |first3=Nicholas |title=Governors Tell Outsiders From 'Hot Zone' to Stay Away as Virus Divides States |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/coronavirus-united-states.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Remote communities ==\nBy March 22, some remote villages were attempting to isolate themselves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/remote-alaska-villages-isolate-themselves-further-in-effort-to-shield-against-coronavirus|title=Remote Alaska Villages Isolate Themselves Further in Effort to Shield Against Coronavirus|last=Hopkins|first=Kyle|date=2020-03-22|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of a COVID-19 case being identified in a remote community, the state plan is to transport the patient to a hub city for treatment rather than dispatching medical workers to the remote area.<ref name=\"villages 1\" /><ref name=\"villages 2\" />\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Alaska<ref name=\"ADHSS\">{{cite web|url= http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/monitoring.aspx |title=Case Counts|publisher=Alaska Department of Health|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated April 18, 2020 \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Community\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchor Point, Alaska|Anchor Point]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n|138\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Chugiak, Anchorage|Chugiak]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Craig, Alaska|Craig]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Delta Junction, Alaska|Delta Junction]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Eagle River, Anchorage|Eagle River]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Fairbanks, Alaska|Fairbanks]]\n|63\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Girdwood, Anchorage, Alaska|Girdwood]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Homer, Alaska|Homer]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Interior - other\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]]\n|24\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kenai, Alaska|Kenai]]\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kodiak, Alaska|Kodiak]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Nome, Alaska|Nome]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[North Pole, Alaska|North Pole]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Palmer, Alaska|Palmer]]\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Petersburg, Alaska|Petersburg]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Seward, Alaska|Seward]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Soldotna, Alaska|Soldotna]]\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sterling, Alaska|Sterling]]\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Yukon\u2013Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska|Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wasilla, Alaska|Wasilla]]\n|10\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''Total'''\n|'''314'''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Age ranges===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+{{nowrap|Alaska COVID-19 cases by age group}}\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | Age\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Cases\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Number\n! scope=\"col\" |Deaths\n|-\n! 80+\n|6\n|0\n|-\n! 70\u201379\n|20\n|5\n|-\n! 60\u201369\n|45\n|1\n|-\n! 50\u201359\n|58\n|1\n|-\n! 40\u201349\n|49\n|0\n|-\n! 30\u201339\n|65\n|2\n|-\n! 20\u201329\n|48\n|0\n|-\n! 10\u201319\n|17\n|0\n|-\n! 0\u20139\n|6\n|0\n|-\n! Total\n|'''314'''\n|'''9'''\n|}\n'''Source:''' ADHSS, April 18, 2020.<ref name=\"ADHSS\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/default.aspx Coronavirus information] from [[Alaska Department of Health and Social Services]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Alaska]]\n[[Category:2020 in Alaska|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Health in Alaska]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Alaska, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Alaska\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 cases in geographical Alaska.jpg\n| legend1         = Map of cases by borough, as of April 18\n{{legend|#FDFEB3|1\u201319}}{{legend|#FCDA74|20\u201359}}{{legend|#B60000|> 60}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Alaska]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n| arrival_date    = March 7, 2020\n| date            = \n| origin          = \n| type            = \n| confirmed_cases = 314\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| hospitalized_cases = 36\n| recovery_cases  = 147\n| deaths          = 9\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://coronavirus.alaska.gov/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Alaska]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska's coronavirus response has escalated as the number of cases has grown. Here's where things stand. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/22/alaskas-coronavirus-response-has-escalated-as-the-number-of-cases-has-grown-heres-where-things-stand/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]'s office declared a state of emergency to ensure all entities have the necessary response resources.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/11/governor-issues-public-health-disaster-emergency-declaration-for-covid-19/|title=Governor Issues Public Health Disaster Emergency Declaration for COVID-19|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The next day, the first case, a foreign national in [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], was announced to the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2020/03/12/first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed-by-alaska-state-public-health-laboratory-is-an-international-resident/|title=First case of COVID-19 confirmed by Alaska State Public Health Laboratory is an international resident|publisher=Alaska Government|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Alaska medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Ketchikan, Alaska, Estados Unidos, 2017-08-16, DD 01.jpg|thumb|Ketchikan, one of the places affected by COVID-19 during the 2020 outbreak in Alaska]]\nIn March 21, 2020, [[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]], a small, coastal town of approximately 8,000 residents located in [[Southeast Alaska]] was determined to have a cluster of six COVID-19 cases. The town [[shelter in place|sheltered in place]] for the following 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Stone |title=Officials announce three more COVID-19 cases in Ketchikan |url=https://www.ktoo.org/2020/03/21/ketchikan-officials-announce-three-more-covid-19-cases/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=[[KRBD]] via [[KTOO-TV]]|date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On March 24, 2020, three more cases of COVID-19 were found in Ketchikan, bringing the total there to nine.<ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATE: Ketchikan confirms 3 new cases of COVID-19 |url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/Ketchikan-confirms-2-new--confirmed-cases-of-COVID-19-569066131.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[KTUU-TV]] |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> The next day, the total cases there reached 11.<ref>{{cite web|first=Eric|last=Stone|url=https://www.krbd.org/2020/03/25/two-new-coronavirus-cases-bring-ketchikans-total-to-11/ |title=Two new coronavirus cases bring Ketchikan's total to 11 |date=26 March 2020|publisher=[[KRBD]]|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On April 1, 2020, the number of positive cases of COVID-19 in Ketchikan rose to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kinyradio.com/news/news-of-the-north/ketchikan-covid-19-cases-rise-to-14-after-new-diagnosis/ |title=Ketchikan COVID-19 cases rise to 14 after new diagnosis |date=April 1, 2020|publisher=[[KINY]]|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Measures==\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] ordered public schools to close from March 16 to 30,<ref>{{cite news |title=Alaska officials close public schools to students through March 30 to limit spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/14/alaska-officials-close-k-12-public-schools-to-students-for-extra-2-weeks-to-limit-spread-of-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\">{{cite news |title=Alaska's statewide school closure is beginning. No one knows quite how it will work. |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/education/2020/03/16/alaskas-statewide-school-closure-is-about-to-begin-no-one-knows-quite-how-it-will-work/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> which was later extended to May 1.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\">{{cite news |last1=Hanlon |first1=Tegan |last2=Ruskin |first2=Liz |last3=Media |first3=Alaska Public |title=State extends Alaska school closures as coronavirus count grows to 14 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/20/state-announces-new-business-closures-for-fairbanks-ketchikan-and-asks-alaskans-to-stop-all-non-essential-travel/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> School districts were advised to find ways to use remote learning, but there was concern about the impact on the youngest students, special ed students, and small and remote areas where online learning is more difficult.<ref name=\"statewide school closure is beginning\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Governor Dunleavy announced the creation of the Alaska Economic Stabilization Team (AEST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/home/covid-19-economy/|title=COVID-19 Alaska Economic Stabilization Team \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, restaurants were restricted to take-out and delivery, and entertainment venues such as movie theaters and gyms were closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ruskin |first1=Liz |title=State bans restaurant dining as Alaska's confirmed coronavirus cases grow to 6 |url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2020/03/17/state-bans-restaurant-dining-as-alaskas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-grow-to-6/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Alaska Public Media |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Mayor of Anchorage]] [[Ethan Berkowitz]] issued an \"emergency hunker down order\" effective March 22.<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some businesses were closed in [[Fairbanks North Star Borough]] and [[Ketchikan Gateway Borough]].<ref name=\"extends Alaska school closures\"/> Some villages restricted air travel.<ref name=\"villages 1\">{{cite news |title=Alaska villages to ban, restrict air travel amid coronavirus |url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Alaska-villages-to-ban-restrict-air-travel-amid-15148159.php |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Hour |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"villages 2\">{{cite news |title=Alaska rural villages begin to ban or severely restrict air travel in hopes of slowing coronavirus |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/rural-alaska/2020/03/20/alaska-rural-villages-begin-to-ban-or-severely-restrict-air-travel-in-hopes-of-slowing-coronavirus/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Anchorage Daily News |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Mike Dunleavy ordered everyone arriving in Alaska to self-quarantine for 14 days upon arrival, effective March 25, with limited exceptions.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Health Mandate |url=https://gov.alaska.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/03232020-SOA-COVID-19-Health-Mandate-010.pdf |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |last2=Bosman |first2=Julie |last3=Bogel-Burroughs |first3=Nicholas |title=Governors Tell Outsiders From 'Hot Zone' to Stay Away as Virus Divides States |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/coronavirus-united-states.html |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Remote communities ==\nBy March 22, some remote villages were attempting to isolate themselves.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/remote-alaska-villages-isolate-themselves-further-in-effort-to-shield-against-coronavirus|title=Remote Alaska Villages Isolate Themselves Further in Effort to Shield Against Coronavirus|last=Hopkins|first=Kyle|date=2020-03-22|website=ProPublica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn the event of a COVID-19 case being identified in a remote community, the state plan is to transport the patient to a hub city for treatment rather than dispatching medical workers to the remote area.<ref name=\"villages 1\" /><ref name=\"villages 2\" />\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Alaska<ref name=\"ADHSS\">{{cite web|url= http://dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/monitoring.aspx |title=Case Counts|publisher=Alaska Department of Health|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated April 18, 2020 \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Community\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchor Point, Alaska|Anchor Point]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]]\n|138\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bethel, Alaska|Bethel]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Chugiak, Anchorage|Chugiak]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Craig, Alaska|Craig]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Delta Junction, Alaska|Delta Junction]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Eagle River, Anchorage|Eagle River]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Fairbanks, Alaska|Fairbanks]]\n|63\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Girdwood, Anchorage, Alaska|Girdwood]]<br>(Anchorage)\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Homer, Alaska|Homer]]\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Interior - other\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]]\n|24\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kenai, Alaska|Kenai]]\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ketchikan, Alaska|Ketchikan]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kodiak, Alaska|Kodiak]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Nome, Alaska|Nome]]\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[North Pole, Alaska|North Pole]]\n|15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Palmer, Alaska|Palmer]]\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Petersburg, Alaska|Petersburg]]\